<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Fri 23 Feb 2007 12:59:53 -0800 (PST)
From: Brent Barrett <salbrent@sbcglobal.net>
Source: Prensa Latina [edited]
<http://www.plenglish.com/article.asp?ID=%7B17FBA3FB-00FD-43F2-9E93-914D2D762AA9%7D&language=E>

The Chilean government is working to reduce the 1st outbreak of anthrax
this year [2007], which was detected 9 days ago [15 Feb 2007], interim
agriculture minister Cecilia Leiva reported. Insisting there was no risk of
contagion to human beings, she said the Agriculture and Cattle Service
(SAG) is taking measures to prevent and control spread of the illness. The
interim ministerial team administered antibiotics to people and vaccinated
100 ovine and bovine animals to prevent new outbreaks.
This 1st case was found in southern Punta Capitana, a small fishing village
of 15 families. Leiva reported that SAG took samples of the dead animal for
laboratory analysis, which confirmed the presence of the _Bacillus
anthracis_, known as Carbunco bacteridiano or "Picada" [in Spanish].
--
