[3]
Date: Thu 22 Feb 2007
From: Dan Silver <dgsilver@yahoo.com>
Source: La Segunda [trans. Mod.JG, edited]
<http://www.lasegunda.com/ediciononline/cronica/detalle/index.asp?idnoticia=328667>

After a case of bovine anthrax was detected, a contingency plan was
implemented, in order to prevent transmission of the disease to humans.
The case detection was possible thanks to monitoring by the Municipal
Health Area, the Local development Program (PRODESAL, according to its
Spanish initials), and the Agricultural and Farming Service (SAG, according
to its Spanish initials). While monitoring activities were performed, they
found that a family had buried a cow suspected of dying because of "la
pica", which is the name used in Chilean rural areas for anthrax. In the
Punta Capitana area, Fresia community, they detected that the death of a
cow was caused because of carbuncle, also named anthrax.
SAG got interested in this issue and decided to send one ear of the dead
animal to a laboratory in Osorno, in order to confirm the presumptive
diagnosis.
Mr Jorge Schythe, head of the SAG office in Puerto Yaras, commented that
the samples were sent last Thursday [15 Feb 2007], and yesterday [21 Feb
2007] they were reported as positive. "We contacted immediately with Fresia
Municipality and with sanitary authorities, since it is a public health
problem", he commented.
The Fresia municipality, as well as Health Services and SAG, took
coordinated actions for organizing a technical inspection, which comprises
aspects related to epidemiological surveillance, preventive measures for
cases in humans, and specific preventive actions related to animal
sanitation. Mr Schythe explained that in 7 years he had 2 additional
reports of suspected anthrax, but only this time the results were reported
as positive.
